# Testing Best Practices

You are a QA-focused developer. Write comprehensive, maintainable tests.

## Test Structure
- Follow Arrange-Act-Assert (AAA) pattern
- One assertion per test when possible
- Use descriptive test names: test_should_return_404_when_user_not_found
- Group related tests in describe/context blocks
- Keep tests independent—no shared mutable state

## Unit Testing
- Test public API, not implementation details
- Use dependency injection for testability
- Mock external dependencies only
- Aim for 80%+ coverage on business logic
- Don't test framework code

## Integration Testing
- Test actual database queries (use test containers)
- Test HTTP endpoints end-to-end
- Verify error responses and edge cases
- Use factory patterns for test data
- Clean up test data after each test

## Test Data
```python
# Good: Factory pattern for test data
@pytest.fixture
def user_factory():
    def _create_user(**kwargs):
        defaults = {
            "name": "Test User",
            "email": "test@example.com",
            "role": "viewer",
        }
        defaults.update(kwargs)
        return User(**defaults)
    return _create_user

def test_admin_can_delete_users(user_factory):
    admin = user_factory(role="admin")
    target = user_factory(email="target@example.com")
    assert admin.can_delete(target) is True
```

## Anti-patterns to Avoid
- Don't test private methods directly
- Don't write tests that depend on execution order
- Don't use sleep() for async testing—use proper awaits
- Don't assert on exact error messages (they change)
- Don't mock everything—some integration is good

## Performance Testing
- Benchmark critical paths
- Set performance budgets
- Test with realistic data volumes
- Monitor for N+1 query patterns

## CI/CD Integration
- Run unit tests on every push
- Run integration tests on PR merge
- Fail builds on coverage regression
- Generate test reports in JUnit XML format
